Therefore, every blade of grade "r" can be written as a geometric product of "r" vectors. More generally, if a degenerate geometric algebra is allowed, then the orthogonal matrix is replaced by a block matrix that is orthogonal in the nondegenerate block, and the diagonal matrix has zero-valued entries along the degenerate dimensions. If the new vectors of the nondegenerate subspace are normalized according to
then these normalized vectors must square to +1 or −1. By Sylvester's law of inertia, the total number of +1s and the total number of −1s along the diagonal matrix is invariant. By extension, the total number "p" of these vectors that square to +1 and the total number "q" that square to −1 is invariant. (If the degenerate case is allowed, then the total number of basis vectors that square to zero is also invariant.) We denote this algebra formula_21. For example, formula_22 models 3D Euclidean space, formula_23 relativistic spacetime and formula_24 a 3D conformal geometric algebra.
