Electrodynamics and special relativity.
In physics, the main applications are the geometric algebra of Minkowski 3+1 spacetime, , called spacetime algebra (STA). or less commonly, , called the algebra of physical space (APS) where is isomorphic to the "even" subalgebra of the 3+1 Clifford algebra, .
While in STA points of spacetime are represented simply by vectors, in APS, points of (3+1)-dimensional spacetime are instead represented by paravectors: a 3-dimensional vector (space) plus a 1-dimensional scalar (time).
In spacetime algebra the electromagnetic field tensor has a bivector representation formula_120. Here, the imaginary unit is the (four-dimensional) volume element, and formula_121 is the unit vector in time direction. Using the four-current formula_122, Maxwell's equations then become
